45–1102","1054–1106":"1054–1106","1091":"1091","1054":"1054","1142":"1142","1163":"1163","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","de 1129 a 1163":"from 1129 to 1163","1159":"1159","1169":"1169","1114":"1114","1102":"1102","1078":"1078","1045":"1045","about 1114":"about 1114","1109":"1109","1108":"1108","Hangest-en-Santerre, Somme, Picardie, França":"Hangest-en-Santerre, Somme, Picardie, France","Hangest-en-Santerre, Somme, Picardy, France":"Hangest-en-Santerre, Somme, Picardie, France","France":"France","Hangest-en-Santerre - Somme - France":"Hangest-en-Santerre, Somme, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hangest","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Upper or Lower Hergest (Herefordshire), a placename of uncertain etymology."],"variants":[{"name":"Hargis","meanings":["English (Essex): perhaps a variant of   Hargest  . Alternatively, an altered form of German or Frisian <b>Harges</b>, which is probably of the same origin as Frisian   Harjes  .","History: The (majority of the) American bearers of the surname <i>Hargis</i> trace their origin to George Hargis, who was transported from England to VA in 1642 and whose grandfather is believed by some to be Louis Harges, a Frenchman from Normandy, supposedly of Danish parentage. The surname <i>Harges</i> is not found neither in France nor in Denmark; it is, however, found in northern Germany, though it is very rare there."]}]},{"name":"Roland","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. In Old French literature it is borne by a legendary Frankish hero, a vassal of Charlemagne, whose exploits are told in the <i>Chanson de Roland</i>. The subject of the poem is Roland's death at the Battle of Roncesvalles in the Pyrenees in  778 , while protecting the rearguard of the Frankish army on its retreat from Spain. Roland is depicted in literature and legend as headstrong and impulsive. His devoted friendship with the prudent  Oliver  is also legendary."],"variants":[{"name":"Rowland","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roland  , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ecuyer Roland de Hangest was born in 1078, in Hangest-en-Santerre, Somme, Picardie, France, his father, Roques de Hangest, was 33 and his mother, Alix de Chaulnes, was 24. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Hortense de Rosières. He died from 1129 to 1163."},"et":{"1078–de 1129 a 1163":"1078–1129 kuni 1163","1078–1163":"1078–1163","1091–1142":"1091–1142","1108–1159":"1108–1159","1109–1163":"1109–1163","1114–1169":"1114–1169","1045–1102":"1045–1102","1054–1106":"1054–1106","1091":"1091","1054":"1054","1142":"1142","1163":"1163","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","de 1129 a 1163":"1129 kuni 1163","1159":"1159","1169":"1169","1114":"1114","1102":"1102","1078":"1078","1045":"1045","about 1114":"umbes 1114","1109":"1109","1108":"1108","Hangest-en-Santerre, Somme, Picardie, França":"Hangest-en-Santerre, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusma